§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We are constantly thinking of the integers as the endpoints
    of equal length segments of a line. ⦉
⦉

§ Discussion ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We commonly associate elements of the integers with the
    endpoints of equal-length segments of a real line. ⦉

  ‖ Take segment $S_0$ of $L$ with endpoints $p$ and $q$. ⦉

  ‖ Associate the point $p$ with $0$. ⦉

  ‖ Associate the point $q$ with $1$. ⦉

  ‖ Take a segment $S_1$ of equal length, non-overlapping with
    $S_0$, who shares the endpoint $q$. ⦉

  ‖ Associate the second endpoint of this segment $2$. ⦉

  ‖ Continue with the rest. ⦉

  ‖ We call the line so formed the ❬integral line❭ of unit
    $S_0$. ⦉
⦉

