§ Integral Distance ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Let $f: 𝗭 → 𝗭$ be defined by $f(a, b) = a - b$ if $a
    > b$ and $f(a, b) = b - a$ if $b > a$. ⦉

  ‖ Notice that $f$ is symmetric: $f(a,b) = f(b, a)$. ⦉

  ‖ The (geometric) interpretation of $f$ is the distance between
    the points associated with the two integers $a, b ∈ 𝗭$ in
    some integral line. ⦉

  ‖ We call $f$ the ❬integral distance❭. ⦉

  ‖ Notice that $f(a, b) > 0$ for all $a, b ∈ 𝗭$. ⦉
⦉

§ Notation ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We denote the distance between $a, b ∈ 𝗭$ by $\abs{a -
    b}$. ⦉
⦉

